						<!-- firstHeading -->
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto">Grammatical gender</span></h1>
			<!-- /firstHeading -->
			<!-- bodyContent -->
			<div id="bodyContent">
								<!-- tagline -->
				<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
				<!-- /tagline -->
								<!-- subtitle -->
				<div id="contentSub"></div>
				<!-- /subtitle -->
																<!-- jumpto -->
				<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<!-- /jumpto -->
								<!-- bodycontent -->
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="dablink">This article is about noun classes.  For uses of language associated with men and women, see <a href="Language_and_gender" title="Language and gender">Language and gender</a>.  For methods of minimizing the use of gendered forms, see <a href="Gender-neutral_language" title="Gender-neutral language">Gender-neutral language</a>.  For other uses, see <a href="Gender_(disambiguation)" title="Gender (disambiguation)">Gender (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:352px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif/350px-Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif" width="350" height="565" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif/525px-Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif/700px-Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Noun_gender_distr_in_various_langs.gif" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Diagrams roughly representing the noun distribution in some languages. The examples include:<br />
1. <i>masculine - feminine<br />
2. masculine - feminine - neuter<br />
3. animate - inanimate</i><br />
Notice in the 1st example how sexless items can be of feminine gender, or how in the 2nd example living beings can be of neuter gender.<br />
Note: The sizes of every set may not be to scale.</div>
</div>
</div>
